Exploring the BRFSS data

Setup

Load packages

library(tidyverse)

Load data

load("brfss2013.RData")

Part 1: Data

The Behavioral Risk Factor Surveillance System (BRFSS) is a phone survey conducted by the CDC in all 50 states and US outlying territories. Respondents are randomly selected, non-institutionalized, adults (18+ only) who picked up land-line or cellphones and took the survey. This is a retrospective observational study with random sampling and not an experiment with random assignment therefore we can assume generalization (with some caveats) but NOT causation. If the study is generalized to the US population as a whole several biases exist: prisoners, children, and those without phones are not included. This study is better generalized to the non-institutionalized, phone-owning, adult population of the US. There is also an opportunity for non-response sample bias as not everyone randomly sampled will respond to a phone survey, especially one with enough questions to create 330 variables. If the non-response bias is strong enough that the sample is no longer representative then the study cannot be generalized to the population.

Here I peeked at the data set

# glimpse(brfss2013)

Part 2: Research questions

Research question 1: I have been having trouble getting my eight hours of sleep recently. Are hours of sleep per night and health outcomes are correlated?

Research question 2: Is there a correlation between time spent working vs sleeping and health outcomes?

Research question 3: Is there a correlation between hours of exercise per week, as defined by a sum of the reported average number of hours spent on respondents two most frequent exercise activities per week, and health outcomes?

Part 3: Exploratory data analysis

Data Preparation

I selected the variables on respondents self evaluation of health, reported hours of sleep per 24 hour period, reported hours of work per week, reported weekly frequency of two different exercise activities, and the usual duration of each.

project_d_f <- brfss2013 %>%
  select(general_health = genhlth, sleep_per_day_hrs = sleptim1, work_per_week_hrs = scntlwk1, activity1_freq = exeroft1, activity2_freq = exeroft2, activity1_duration_hmm = exerhmm1, activity2_duration_hmm = exerhmm2)

We can see from the data that there does not appear to be any strong correlation between sleep per night and health outcomes. The mean does show a slight positive correlation between sleep and health. This is however not reflected in the more robust median, except when it jumps from 6 to 7 going from “Poor” health to “Fair” health. It is worth noting that the spread of hours of sleep is higher than any other response, by both standard deviation and IQR, which is likely, at least in part, attributable to the number of “Poor” responses being less than half that of the next least popular response. To answer the question I’d say there is a very weak correlation between hours of sleep and reported health.

Again, this was a retrospective observational study with random sampling and not an experiment with random assignment therefore I did not assume causation. The relationship in the variables may be caused by a confounding variable. It is also worth noting potential issues with this data and assumptions made. In this case there were some extreme responses for hours slept, including multiple respondents who reported sleeping 24 hours a day (Which I’d argue would make it difficult to answer a phone survey), and we are relying on each respondents own self evaluation of health.

Sleep needs to be in the unit hours/week so it matches our work variable, to achieve this I created a new variable called sleep_per_week_hrs. It assumes that respondents sleep the same number of hours every night, which could be a source of error. For seeing if someone sleeps more than works a ratio of the two would be useful. Sleep to work ratio raises some issues because it divides by work per week hours which can be zero. To avoid dividing by zero I instead calculated work per sleep ratio and called it work_sleep_ratio.

project_d_f <- project_d_f %>%
  mutate(sleep_per_week_hrs = sleep_per_day_hrs * 7, work_sleep_ratio = work_per_week_hrs / sleep_per_week_hrs)

This faceted histogram shows how the distributions of work_sleep_ratio for each factor in general_health. In order to show more of the bulk of the distribution some outliers are cropped out by the scaling of the plot.

    geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.2, boundary = 0) +

Research question 3:

Question 3 required calculating a total time spent exercising calculated as a function of four variables. Those were the frequency respondents partook in activities 1 and 2, and the amount of time spent on each activity per session. I examined each in turn before making any calculations.

Activity frequency recorded the responses to the question “How many times per week or per month did you take part in this activity during the past month?” for each of the two exercise activities the respondents indicated they most frequently participated in. Answers given as weekly frequency are coded with a 1 in the hundreds place, those given as monthly frequency were recorded with a 2 in the hundreds place.

##                    Title      n min Q1 median  Q3 max
## 1 activity2_duration_hmm 208124   0 30     45 130 959
# here I output short summaries of each of the new variables to get a feel for what I am working with.

Here I calculated hours exercised per week as a variable called exercise_per_week_hrs. Working backwards:

When examining the data the number of responses for activity 1 and activity 2 are different (more than one hundred thousand more responses were recorded for activity 1), this means that there are many cases where time spent on activity 1 has an integer value and activity 2 has a value of NA. In R math operations done with NA return NA so the code for this calculation had to be written such that if one of the values was NA the total value, exercise_per_week_hrs, would be set equal to the other value.

The total time spent on activities that exercise_per_week_hrs summed were calculated as activity1_per_week_hrs and activity2_per_week_hrs as the product of activity_freq_week and activity_duration_hmm.

activity_duration_hmm for each activity was converted to hours by taking the result of floor division of activity_duration_hmm, examined above, by 100 then adding to that the remainder of that same division and further dividing that value (representing minutes) by 60. This was stored in activity_duration_hmm for each activity.

activity_freq_week was calculated by determining whether the value of activity_freq was in units of times per week or times per month by checking whether it was between 100 and 200 or 200 and 300. If it was already in weekly format it was left unchanged, if it was in monthly format it was converted through division by four (this assumes exercise per month was evenly distributed by week), if it was neither a value of NA was returned.

project_d_f <- project_d_f %>%
  mutate(activity1_freq_week = if_else(activity1_freq >= 100 & activity1_freq < 200, activity1_freq - 100, if_else(activity1_freq >= 200 & activity1_freq < 300, (activity1_freq - 200) / 4, as.numeric(NA)))) %>%
  mutate(activity2_freq_week = if_else(activity2_freq >= 100 & activity2_freq < 200, activity2_freq - 100, if_else(activity2_freq >= 200 & activity2_freq < 300, (activity2_freq - 200) / 4, as.numeric(NA)))) %>%
# activity frequency is stored such that the value right of the 100s place of values 0-199 represent times per week while the value right of the 100s place of values greater than 200 represent times per month. Here activity frequency was converted so all values represented weekly frequency.
  mutate(activity1_duration_hr = activity1_duration_hmm %/% 100 +  ((activity1_duration_hmm %% 100) / 60)) %>%
  mutate(activity2_duration_hr = activity2_duration_hmm %/% 100 +  ((activity2_duration_hmm %% 100) / 60)) %>%
# activity duration is stored with hours in the hundreds place and the digits to the right representing minutes. Here each activity time is converted to straight hours.
  mutate(activity1_per_week_hrs = activity1_freq_week * activity1_duration_hr) %>%
  mutate(activity2_per_week_hrs = activity2_freq_week * activity2_duration_hr) %>%
# here the total hours per week spent on each activity are calculated by multiplying frequency by duration
  mutate(exercise_per_week_hrs = if_else(!is.na(activity1_per_week_hrs) & !is.na(activity2_per_week_hrs), activity1_per_week_hrs + activity2_per_week_hrs, if_else(!is.na(activity1_per_week_hrs), activity1_per_week_hrs, activity2_per_week_hrs)))
# Both values of activity_per_week_hrs were added for a total value per week called exercise_per_week_hrs using if_else statements to ensure that NA values did not override the value if either activity had a frequency of NA.

I noticed that there were some responses greater than 168 hours, which is impossible without time travel, so I went back and made responses greater than 168 hours per week (the total hours in a week) NA. While I’m still skeptical about responses above 84 hours per week, or 12 hours per day, I will treat them as valid responses because they are at least possible and it is dangerous to just go deleting outliers.

project_d_f <- project_d_f %>%
  mutate(exercise_per_week_hrs = if_else(exercise_per_week_hrs <= 168, exercise_per_week_hrs, as.numeric(NA)))

Were exercise and health correlated? They, were positively correlated and strongly so as reflected by the mean and median time spent exercising going up as health gets better. This trend is clearly visible on the side by side boxplots and to a lesser extent on the faceted histograms.

Again, this was a retrospective observational study with random sampling and not an experiment with random assignment therefore I did not assume causation. The relationship in the variables may be caused by a confounding variable. It is also worth noting potential issues with this data and assumptions made. In this case there were some extreme responses for hours slept, I assumed the respondents only participated the two types of exercise they reported and that they were accurate in their reporting, and I was relying on each respondents own self evaluation of health.
